ity. Negative: know-it-all, hot temper (cooperation). No explicit stress handling, but problem solving and concentration help. Reliability good (responsibility). Technical competence decent (problem solving). Cooperation issues.\n\nWe need best overall. Which candidate has least cooperation negatives? All have some. B's nasty remarks is severe. A's show-off and not open to ideas also negative. C's egocentric and communication difficulty also negative. D's hot temper and know-it-all also negative. Which is worst? Probably B's nasty remarks is direct hostility, which is severe. D's hot temper also severe. A's show-off maybe less severe. C's egocentric also severe.\n\nConsider strengths: D has many technical strengths (problem solving, concentration, responsibility) and handles unexpected events. No explicit calmness but problem solving suggests. Cooperation negatives: hot temper and know-it-all. Could be mitigated? But still.\n\nA has strong leadership, anticipation, spatial vision, but not open to new ideas (could hinder learning). Show-off may affect crew morale.\n\nB has conscientiousness, stress handling, weather, computer, but memory weak and nasty remarks.\n\nC has quick decisions, calm in crisis, tech understanding, but communication issues, egocentric, not willing to further education.\n\nOverall, D seems balanced: responsibility, problem solving, concentration, handling unexpected events. Cooperation negatives are hot temper and know-it-all, but maybe less directly hostile than nasty remarks. Also D lacks explicit calmness under pressure but problem solving and concentration may cover.\n\nThus provisional preference: Candidate D.\n\nConfidence moderate.\n\nNow produce output.\n\nNeed to include evidence from others: none yet.\n\nAlternatives considered: A, B, C.\n\nMain tradeoff: cooperation negatives vs technical strengths.\n\nRemaining uncertainty: severity of D's hot temper and its impact on crew.\n\nWhat would change vote: evidence that D's temper leads t